@node intro "Introduction"
This is an email program using POP3 and SMTP.

Iris is a figure from Greek mythology. Literally, the word means "rainbow".
Iris is a messager of the gods. She comes down as a rainbow. This program
belongs in the divine company of Thor, Pegasus and Eudora, and therefore
this name was chosen.

Features:

* You can double click on URLs to @{"browse" link browsewww} them.
* You can double click on email addresses to mail to them.
* It does not use MUI.
* It is stable.
* It supports Eudora's and Exchange's @{"Priority" link priority} and @{"Return-Receipt" link rr} header
  fields.
* It has excellent @{"filter capabilities" link cf_filters}.
* Extensive use of multitasking.
* Keyboard shortcuts for most functions.
* Excellent for using a POP account from more than one location, for instance
  work and home.
* It has an @{"ARexx interface" link arexx}.
* Multiple signatures.
* Multiple selection in @{"message list" link readmail}.
* Search function in message list and message

Iris is written in AmigaE (v3.3a). AmigaE is similar to C, but it has some
additional features like exception handling and it compiles incredibly fast.
AmigaE is copyright Wouter van Oortmerssen. Iris uses @{"BGUI" link bgui} for its
graphical user interface.
@endnode

@node require "Prerequisites"
Required:
* TCP/IP stack with bsdsocket.library version 3 or higher interface
  (AmiTCP 3/4, Genesis, Miami, TermiteTCP), or one with socket.library
  interface (e.g. AS225) with Finale Development's emulation library at
  http://www.finale-dev.com/archives/bsdsocket46.lha. The program has only
  been tested with Miami 3.2b.
* AmigaOS 2.04 (V37) or higher
* @{"bgui.library" link bgui} V41 and bgui_popbutton.gadget (included)

Recommended:
* A MagicWB-like screen palette
* AmigaOS 3.5 :-)
@endnode

@node discl "Disclaimer"
I am not responsible for any damage this software may cause, including but
not limited to lost mail or lost files.

Jilles Tjoelker makes no representations concerning either the
merchantability of this software or the suitability of this software for
any particular purpose. It is provided "as is" without express or implied
warranty of any kind.

@endnode

@node install "Installation"
An Installer script is provided that takes care of all necessary installation
steps.

The script performs the following tasks:

* Installs the program.
* Installs the guide.
* Installs the correct script from @{"BrowseWWWscripts" link browsewww}, if openurl.library
  is not installed.
* Installs the ARexx scripts.
* Copies icons.
* Installs the bgui.library (with version check).
* Installs the bgui_popbutton.gadget class (with version check).

If you don't have AmigaOS V38+, the variable TZ must be set in order to
enable Iris to include the correct timezone in the Date: header field.
Menno Tjoelker's Daylight Saving Time solution is supported: if the DST
environment variable contains "DST", 60 minutes are subtracted.

You must do a @{"minimal configuration" link qstart}.
@endnode

@node qstart "Quick start"
To be able to use Iris, you must at least do a minimal configuration.

* From the menu Configuration, select Config.... Choose '1. Network'.
* Fill in all the gadgets.
* Choose 'Composing'.
* Edit your default signature, which will be added to messages you send.
* Click on the Save button to store the configuration. 
@endnode   

@node compose "Composing mail"
"Reply to all" includes all Cc's from the old message in the new one.
When you select "New message", "Reply", "Reply to all" or double-click on
an email address, the @{"$EDITOR" link editor} will be invoked. It is important that you
save first before exiting. If you don't do this, the operation will be
cancelled. Then a window will pop up, where you can set headers. Watch out:
you cannot type multiple addresses in the "Edit address" gadget! You can
choose a signature too. If you don't want a signature, leave the
"Signature" gadget blank.

The program generates the following headers (in this order):
To: & Cc: Contents of the Recipients listview, each address on a separate line
From: config.emailaddr
Subject: Subject gadget
X-Mailer: Iris V... registered/demo - Amiga mailer by Jilles Tjoelker
Date: @{i}for example@{ui} Tue, 11 Nov 1997 11:32 +0100 <- from Locale & $DST
                                                           or TZ ENV variable
MIME-Version: 1.0
Message-ID: <seconds.micros@iris.processaddress> <- in hex without prefix
@{i}if registered:@{ui} X-Registered-To: keyfile.name (keyfile.regid)
@{i}if RR gadget:@{ui} Return-Receipt-To: <config.emailaddr>
@{i}if RR gadget:@{ui} Disposition-Notification-To: <config.emailaddr>
@{i}if HighPri gadget:@{ui} X-Priority: 1 (Very High)
@{i}if HighPri gadget:@{ui} Importance: high
@{i}all headers from the Extra headers list@{ui}
@{i}all other MIME stuff@{ui}
@endnode

@node readmail "Reading mail"
@{b}Examples of searching in the message list:@{ub}

1. Delete all messages except for those that have something to do with
RealAudio: Excluding on, case sensitive on, search for 'RA'; case sensitive
off, interaction 'and', search for 'realaudio', close; delete

2. Select all messages: Excluding on, search for '' (DelFolder.irx is a
faster way to delete all messages in a folder.)

3. Look for messages from or to Tjoelker: Excluding off, search for
'Tjoelker'. You'll need to do this again when you've read a message.

@{b}Controls which may not be immediately clear:@{ub}

Sort on ID: This effectively means: date. These 32bit IDs are given in
numerical order by Iris. They have nothing to do with Message-ID or UIDL!

Multiselect: This can only be used with "Mark...", "Delete", "Move...",
"Archive" and some ARexx scripts. Other things only use one message.

@{i}buttons and hot-keys:@{ui}

1. You can cancel these keys by pressing SHIFT or ESC while the key is still
   pressed.
2. The texts after the "=" signs are the filenames in the @{"Buttons drawer" link bdesign}
   and are shown below the buttons when the USELABELS tooltype in the Check
   icon is set.

(0=Check) c: check for new mail and send mail
(1=NewMsg) n: compose a new message
(2=Reply) r: reply
(3=ReplyAll) t: reply to "Reply-To" and all "Cc" addresses
(4=Forward) m: forward
(5=Prev) -: previous folder/message
(6=ToList) l: show list (message text -> message list -> folder list)
(7=Next) +: next folder/message
(8=Sort) o: select sort key
(9=Delete) d: delete message
(10=Save) s: save the contents of the body listview
(11=Print) p: print the contents of the body listview
(12=ToAddrBook) a: add the From: address to the address book
(13=Search) f: search in the message or the list
(14=ShowHdr) h: show headers yes/no

These keys cannot be cancelled:

DEL: delete message
@{i}on the message list page:@{ui}
left/right: next/previous folder
up/downЙ: next/previous message; deselect all entries except one
return/enter/double-click: go to the message page
@{i}on the message page:@{ui}
left/rightЙ: next/previous message
up/downЙ: move up/down the active line
numeric keypad 1/2/3/7/8/9: scroll through the message
return/enter/double-click: do something with a line:
  ...http://...   @{"Start Web browser" link browsewww}  \\ The first one in
  ...@...         @{"Send e-mail" link compose   }        / the line is used.
  white text      save attachment (last line -> no effect)

Й with shift is page, with alt is extreme

@{b}The Flag column@{ub}
* means unread, S means unsent, space (the default) means nothing special.

@{b}The List/Rebuild item@{ub}

This item will reexamine all messages in this folder, taking the file names
from the hidden field, so all email addresses will be removed from
name-address couples (if they were still there from before V1.4), all dates
will be added and all headers that you may have changed via Message/Edit
will be updated in the list.

@{b}The Message/Archive and Message/Restore archive items@{ub}

An archive is associated with each folder. Archived messages are not in the
list. This decreases the delay when changing to large folders. Archived
messages can only be accessed with the "Restore archive" item (or the
@{"RESTOREARC ARexx command" link arexx}). Be warned that they take the same amount of disk
space. Note that using a separate folder for archiving is still possible.
@endnode

@node editor "EDITOR environment variable"
This variable should contain a command to call an editor. It is important
that the editor runs synchronously, otherwise the program will detect that
you had not saved and cancel the operation. Most editors do work
synchronously.

A well-known exception is CygnusEd. It has another difficulty: the
activator program needs to find the real program in some cases. If
the programs "CED" and "ED" are installed in C: (including
multiassignments), you can set the environment variable EDITOR to "ed
-sticky". The "ED" program (I mean that of CygnusEd, not of Commodore) may
be located elsewhere if you change the variable accordingly, but the "CED"
program may not.

If the "CED" program is not in C:, it is necessary to create a small script
file:

<<< CUT HERE >>>
.K ARGS/F
path work:cygnused ; or whereever it is located
work:cygnused/ed -sticky <ARGS>
<<< CUT HERE >>>

Set $EDITOR to, for instance, "execute work:cygnused/ed.script". (The
filename of the script may differ.)

Do not try to avoid these problems by running the "CED" program directly -
it will not work as it needs 8192 bytes stack, so a script file cannot be
avoided. Furthermore, its switches are different and you may get requesters
saying that CygnusEd is already in memory.

How to set the variable to a value:

Open a shell and type these commands:

setenv editor <value>
copy env:editor envarc:

The second command makes the change permanent, otherwise it is lost upon
reset or power-down.

If the EDITOR ENV variable does not exist, Iris will use Ed (without any
options).
@endnode

@node progdir "Information about PROGDIR:"
PROGDIR: is a special "device" name, a bit like an assign, but different for
each process. It refers to the directory the program has been loaded from,
no matter whether it has been started from Workbench or CLI. Commands which
have been made resident do not have PROGDIR.

AmigaDOS and ARexx scripts cannot use PROGDIR. The programs started from
them can use it, of course. Writing something like "Copy PROGDIR:file RAM:"
will either try to copy C:file (or whereever Copy is located) to RAM: or
display a requester asking to insert the volume 'progdir' in any drive. In
ARexx scripts, the command 'PARSE SOURCE . . . f .' will return the
filename of the script (full path) in the variable f. (According to my ARexx
manual (3.0), this was not true of older versions of ARexx, but those
"older versions" may be older than the version included with AmigaOS 2.0.)

The PROGDIR: in script names in the @{"user menu" link cf_user_menu} is different, because Iris
makes a special check for it. That's also the reason for the restrictions
in its use.

Example: If the Iris program is in the drawer Work:Iris,
PROGDIR:Mail/Folders.cfg will be resolved (only for Iris, for other
programs it may be different) to Work:Iris/Mail/Folders.cfg.

New for V2.1: @{"GETPROGDIR ARexx command" link arexx}
@endnode

@node mcheck "Mail checking"
Iris does not have a built-in mechanism to regularly check whether new mail
has arrived. This function is realised by an ARexx script, Poll.irx. To
enable this function, double-click the icon after starting TCP/IP and Iris.
An easier way is @{"putting it in the user menu" link cf_gui}.
The script will now poll the post office every 3 minutes. You can change this
to any value you like. At the same time, queued mail is sent. The script
will exit automatically if Iris or TCP/IP stops.

Warning: Some people have reported AWeb crashes just when their mailer (not
Iris) was checking for new mail. It is not guaranteed that Iris does not
cause this type of problem, as the opening of a window causes extra
input.device load and it and the usage of the network take memory.

@{"Receiving via SMTP" link smtpd}
@endnode

@node smtpd "SMTP daemon received mail"
On the request of Patrick James, a script has been added that enables you to
load mail received by smtpd into Iris.
In "inetd.conf" the following line must be added:

@{b}smtp	stream	tcp nowait root amitcp:serv/in.smtpd smtpd <parms> @{ub}

where <parms> must be:

@{b}rmail "rx AmiTCP:Iris/IrisRMail.irx %s" @{ub}

Any incoming message will be fed to Iris now.
Warning: this script has not been tested in real life yet.
@endnode

@node cf_network "Configuration: Network page"
@{".mailcap file" link cf_mailcap}
@{b}Network@{ub} @{"Composing" link cf_composing} @{"GUI" link cf_gui} @{"User menu" link cf_user_menu} @{"Folders" link cf_folders} @{"Filters" link cf_filters}

E-Mail address, real name, POP server, SMTP server, Username, Password:
Fill these in. POP server is usually pop3.@{i}provider@{ui}, pop.@{i}provider@{ui} or
mail.@{i}provider@{ui}. SMTP server is usually smtp.@{i}provider@{ui} or mail.@{i}provider@{ui}. Username
is often the part of your email address before the at-sign.

Type: Selects the method which Iris will use to authenticate to the server:

  * Plain: sends the username and password over the network in the clear,
           using the USER and PASS commands. An attacker that can monitor
           traffic can easily obtain your password. Unfortunately, many
           servers require its use.

  * APOP: uses the APOP command to avoid sending the password in the clear.
          For this to work, a so-called challenge in angle brackets must be
          present in the server's greeting. This greeting can be found in
          the first line in the old communication window, and in the first
          line of the file RAM:IrisPOP.log in V2.2 (only if a connection to
          the POP server has been made since the last reboot). Note that
          APOP may fail even though this challenge is present. For example
          the server may not be able to verify the APOP command because it
          doesn't have the required data (it needs access to the plaintext
          password, a weakness of APOP). Also note that although an
          attacker can't directly get the password by eavesdropping, he can
          check whether the password is a certain text, so avoid
          easy-to-guess passwords.

          Example of a greeting with APOP challenge:
          +OK Foobar POP3 at your service <123.456@foobar.com>

  * CRAM-MD5: is quite similar to APOP. However, support for CRAM-MD5
              cannot be detected easily. There is a command for it, CAPA,
              but it's not implemented in many servers, nor in Iris.
              Therefore, you can only try it. CRAM-MD5 does not require
              that the server store the password in the clear, but if the
              server is compromised, information can be obtained which
              allows the attacker to masquerade as you to any CRAM-MD5
              accounts with the same password. As with APOP, an attacker
              can check whether the password is a certain text by
              eavesdropping, so avoid easy-to-guess passwords. The
              password should be at least sixteen characters long.

Both APOP and CRAM-MD5 use @{"MD5" link md5}.

Note that none of the mechanisms protect against active attackers, who, for
instance, change the data flowing on the connection, or hijack the
connection (you are disconnected and they take over the connection to the
POP server). All mail is also sent in the clear. It is possible (but not
with Iris) to use TLS to protect and encrypt the connection to the server,
but the encryption does not really make sense, since the mail is stored
there in the clear (not that anyone can read it, but your system
administrator and hackers can) and highly likely was also put in there
after a transfer in the clear. E-mail should be considered a postcard. For
good security, use an end-to-end mechanism such as PGP.

Delete mail from server: If checked, the mail will be deleted immediately
after downloading.

Only new mail: If checked, only the new mail will be downloaded. This uses
the optional UIDL command of POP3. Most servers support it, but if it
generates errors you'll have to turn it off. When this option is off, the
UIDLs will not be recorded. When this option is on, a file "@{"PROGDIR" link progdir}:Mail/UIDL"
will be created. UIDLs are unique IDs for each message, which are never
reused for the same mailbox. They can be up to 70 characters long.

Keep conn. windows: The connection windows indicate progress of sending and
receiving mail. This checkbox decides whether they should close
automatically after the operation has been completed successfully. If an
error has occured, they remain open in any case.

Confirm messages >10K: Downloads messages only partially (first 20 lines).
It only works when "Only new mail" is on, and additionally needs support
for the TOP command (usually not a problem). When you want to download the
entire message, use the menu item "Message/POP server/Mark for retrieval",
then get mail. Caution: "Delete all mail on server" also deletes partially
fetched messages! For this reason, the new mail requester shows the number
of partially downloaded messages. If you use "Mark for retrieval" and then
immediately "Delete all mail on server", the message is downloaded and then
deleted. If "Delete all mail on server" encounters new messages, they are
handled in the usual way, and deleted unless they have been fetched
partially. Currently, if a partial message is fully downloaded, the full
message is put at the top of the list. Warning: avoid having this checkbox,
the "Delete mail on server" checkbox and the "Only new mail" checkbox all
three on.

UIDL filename: This is used in conjunction with @{"multiple configurations" link mconfig}
referring to multiple POP accounts. It is only used if the "Only new mail"
checkbox is on.

@endnode

@node cf_composing "Configuration: Composing page"
@{".mailcap file" link cf_mailcap}
@{"Network" link cf_network} @{b}Composing@{ub} @{"GUI" link cf_gui} @{"User menu" link cf_user_menu} @{"Folders" link cf_folders} @{"Filters" link cf_filters}

Quote header, quote prefix: These are used to quote in replies.
--> ex. 1 "On %d, %a wrote about %b:%n%n"/"> "
--> ex. 2 "+-----%n|%n| From: %f%n| Subject: %s%n| Date: %d %t%n|%n"/"| "
Note that, differently from other email programs, a space is not added
implicitly after the quote prefix.

Default signature: This allows you to change the default signature
filename. The file can also be edited.

Edit addressbook: This duplicates a function in the Config menu of the main
window.

Taglines:

Taglines can be enabled or disabled for every message, the checkbox here is
just the default.

For the "Tagline file" gadget, there is no filerequester available (sorry).

The correct settings for the Single-line/Multi-line and Separator gadgets
can be determined by looking at the file's contents.

There are no tagline files included with Iris, but almost any tagline (or
cookie) file should be usable.

@endnode

@node cf_gui "Configuration: GUI page"
@{".mailcap file" link cf_mailcap}
@{"Network" link cf_network} @{"Composing" link cf_composing} @{b}GUI@{ub} @{"User menu" link cf_user_menu} @{"Folders" link cf_folders} @{"Filters" link cf_filters}

Column Weights:
With these you can change the relative width of the columns of the message
list window.

Fonts:
With these you can change the fonts used for the message list and the
message text. Since V1.10 these fonts are used immediately. Usage of a
proportional font for the message text will ruin tables. Topaz 8 may be too
wide for the message list; better choices may be XEN 8 or 9 or (X)Helvetica
11. However, text output in Topaz 8 or 9 is somewhat faster than output in
other fonts. Note that for odd font heights, BGUI adds a pixel of spacing.
For example, fonts of size 9 and 10 do not differ in their number of lines
that fit on the screen.

Not in the GUI: @{"How to design your own buttons" link bdesign}
@endnode

@node cf_user_menu "Configuration: User menu page"
@{".mailcap file" link cf_mailcap}
@{"Network" link cf_network} @{"Composing" link cf_composing} @{"GUI" link cf_gui} @{b}User menu@{ub} @{"Folders" link cf_folders} @{"Filters" link cf_filters}

User menu:
Here you can configure the user menu. Keeping the @{"PROGDIR:" link progdir} path will enable
Iris to start the scripts even when its current directory is different.
Note: this will only work if PROGDIR: is the first in the name. Quotes make
it impossible and a second script separated with a semicolon cannot use
this feature either. You cannot use spaces in the names of scripts (an
ARexx limitation). ARexx commands are processed by the instance of Iris
that started the script, unless dictated otherwise. Replace the 'address
iris' line with 'if substr(address(),1,4)~="IRIS" then address iris' and
store address() if you ever use another address.
@endnode

@node cf_folders "Configuration: Folders page"
@{".mailcap file" link cf_mailcap}
@{"Network" link cf_network} @{"Composing" link cf_composing} @{"GUI" link cf_gui} @{"User menu" link cf_user_menu} @{b}Folders@{ub} @{"Filters" link cf_filters}

Preset list (pattern): The left and right buttons are only able to reach
folders whose names match this pattern (case-insensitively unlike normal
folder names). Patterns with an error or patterns which don't match any
names are ignored. The list button can always be used to go to any folder.
The restriction can be temporarily removed with the menu option "Use preset
list". The primary use of this feature is with @{"multiple configurations" link multicfg}.

Edit folder list: This allows you to edit the folder list. In fact, it's
a separate program, but don't start it yourself, usually, as this button
will also cause Iris to update its internal list of folders. When changing
a folder from in to out or vice versa, it is necessary to do a rebuild on
it.

@endnode

@node cf_filters "Configuration: Filters page"
@{".mailcap file" link cf_mailcap}
@{"Network" link cf_network} @{"Composing" link cf_composing} @{"GUI" link cf_gui} @{"Folders" link cf_folders} @{b}Filters@{ub}

On this page you can create and delete filters. You can change the order of
the entries in the listview with the drag-and-drop mechanism. The size of
the columns can be changed by dragging the separating lines. Double-click
on a filter to edit it.

The gadgets in the "Edit folder" window:
All these strings except To folder are matched case-insensitively.
@{u}From:@{uu} this AmigaDOS pattern is matched against the contents of the From
field. If "##" is in it, the address book will be searched for the address
instead.
@{u}To:@{uu} this AmigaDOS pattern is matched against the To header field.
Again "##" means address book.
@{u}Subject:@{uu} this AmigaDOS pattern is matched against the Subject
header field.
@{u}Body:@{uu} the whole body of the message will be searched for this
substring. It can be slow for long messages.
@{u}To folder:@{uu} the message will be moved to this folder, if all above
conditions meet. Empty fields are ignored. The type of this folder (in/out)
is important: only messages of the correct type will be checked.

Examples: (/ separates fields)
1) ##////Inbox                       -> puts mail from people in the
					address book into the inbox.
2) /friend@public.com///JUNK-MAIL    -> puts some spam into JUNK-MAIL
3) #?@hotmail.com////JUNK-MAIL	     -> much spam comes from HotMail
4) //#?Iris#?//Iris		     -> puts messages about Iris in the
					Iris folder. Watch out: if this filter
					is located below 1, filter 1 takes
					precedence.
5) ////JUNK-MAIL		     -> this must be located below 1 and
					puts mail from unknown senders into
					JUNK-MAIL (always matches, any
					In-filters below it are ignored!)

Look in the sample configuration file for more examples.
@endnode

@node cf_mailcap ".mailcap file"
The .mailcap file must be located in the same directory as the Iris
executable. It is only read at startup.

The general format is: @{i}type@{ui}; @{i}command@{ui} [;@{i}opt_params@{ui}]

@{i}type@{ui}: e.g. image/gif. image/* matches any image type and will
cause any following image/#? lines to be ignored.

@{i}command@{ui}: Command to execute for viewing the type; %s is replaced
by the file name upto four times. You can separate multiple commands with
'\\n' (backslash lowercase N) (this may not work with other programs). The
AmigaShell limits the total length of the command to 510 characters (with
substitution, '\\n' is 1 character).

@{i}opt_params@{ui}: not yet used by Iris. It can be "edit=@{i}command@{ui}"

Use '\\' (one backslash) to force characters to be taken literally or to
break long lines ('\\' followed by a linefeed is discarded). The maximum
line length is around 1000. Lines beginning with "#" are comments. When a
type is not found, the information found for "application/octet-stream" is
used. If that's not available either, the file is saved and an error message
displays where.

There are currently no error messages for syntactical errors in the
.mailcap file. There is, however, the @{"WRITEMAILCAP ARexx command" link arexx}, which can
be called, for example, with a separate @{"user menu entry" link cf_user_menu} or from
@{"IrisShell.irx" link rx_examples}.

@{b}Example mailcap file:@{ub}

# mailcap file
text/plain; work:tools/muchmore %s
text/*; work:tools/muchmore %s; edit=work:cygnused/ced %s

# extra types for type requester
image/gif; work:tools/fastview %s
image/jpeg; work:tools/fastview %s
image/png; work:tools/fastview %s
image/*; work:tools/fastview %s; edit=ppaint:ppaint %s

application/octet-stream; sys:utilities/multiview screen %s;\\
 edit=work:cygnused/ced %s

Note: old versions (<3.0) of AmigaGuide will display two backslashes in
places where there should be just one.
@endnode

@node bdesign "Button design"
The buttons are stored in directories "Storage/..._Buttons" as normal icons,
so you can edit them very easily. A few hints are necessary, however:

* You'd better make them Project icons, even though the type doesn't matter
  for Iris, because CLI commands, like sort, search and delete, cause software
  failure $87000004 if they're started from WB, which can happen if you
  accidentally double-click on a Tool icon.
* If you want to see if you have selected a button, you must supply
  a second image. Complement and backfill are not supported.
* If Iris fails with "Could not open window", try to set the tooltype
  "USETWOROWS" in the Check icon of the new button set. If it doesn't even
  work with that, then you can try (V2.0) the tooltype "USEVIEWGROUP",
  which makes the toolbar horizontally scrollable. Note that BGUI bugs may
  show up when using this.
* The tooltype "SPACING" indicates the spacing between buttons, horizontal
  as well as vertical in pixels. The negative values -1, -2 and -3 mean
  BGUI defaults narrow, normal and wide, respectively.
* If you have forgotten a button, a black rectangle, which will become white
  on selection, will appear in its place.
* The tooltype "USELABELS" places texts under the buttons. It may be
  necessary to use "USETWOROWS" and/or "USEVIEWGROUP" to fit this on the
  screen.
* You can use NewIcons, but it will look horrible on another screen.
* Send them to me, or upload them to Aminet!
@endnode

@node browsewww "Iris and browsing the Web"
By double-clicking on a line of a message which contains an HTTP URL, you
can view the URL with your browser. To use this, you need either
to have openurl.library in LIBS: or to copy an ARexx script that is specific
for your browser. @{"The Installer script" link install} does this for you. The script
should be put in the same directory as Iris and named BrowseWWW.rexx. It has
one argument: the URL. It might be necessary to change the path where your
browser can be found in the scripts.

The other way around, a web browser can call Iris to send an email message.
The general call is: Iris MAILTO <email address>
In AWeb, you must define this under Network settings/Extern/mailto: (watch
out: click in the gadget first, and press return when you are ready!)
In other browsers, use a similar method. Currently, Iris does not support
setting the body from the command line (for things like mailto: forms or
replying in email to a news article) and AWeb doesn't support using an
external mailer for these things either.
@endnode

@node multicfg "Multiple configurations"
How to create a new configuration:

In Iris:

* Change the configuration (except for the folder list) and select 'Use'.
* Select 'Export...' from the Configuration menu.
* If the directory of the file requester is not the directory Iris is in,
  type '@{"PROGDIR:" link progdir}' in the Drawer gadget.
* Save the configuration as '@{i}name@{ui}.cfg'. It's wise to include
  "Iris" in this name.
* Select 'Last saved default' from the Configuration menu to restore your
  default configuration.

Workbench (also for Toolmanager):

* Duplicate the icon 'Iris_project' and rename it. If it's not present,
  load the 'Iris' icon in an icon editor, change the type to Project and
  save it under a new name. This name need not be the same as the name you
  saved the configuration under.
* In Information, the default tool must be Iris (with path if the icon is
  in a different drawer) and a tooltype 'CONFIG=@{i}name@{ui}', in which @{i}name@{ui}
  is the name you saved the configuration under, but without 'PROGDIR:' and
  without '.cfg'.

CLI:

* The command option CONFIG=@{i}name@{ui} (with @{i}name@{ui} just as above) selects another
  configuration.

To use the new configuration, quit any other copy of Iris you may have
running before double-clicking the project icon. You can also use the
@{"SETCFGNAME ARexx command" link arexx}. The script @{"SelectCfg.irx" link rx_examples} is an easy way
to do it.

IMPORTANT: Do not use the "Configuration/Import..." option to select a
configuration. That item is only meant to import a configuration, and will
not change the filename for Save and Use.

These configurations can also be 'Use'd separately. The filename for Save
is PROGDIR:@{i}name@{ui}.cfg, the filename for Use is ENV:@{i}name@{ui}.cfg. The
default for @{i}name@{ui} is 'Iris', yielding the same behaviour as earlier
versions.

The tooltype CONFIG can also be used on the Iris program icon. In this case
it takes effect whenever Iris is started from Workbench and no project icon
overrides the setting. The CONFIG CLI option has the same effect.

As of V2.1, the current CONFIG setting is shown in the title bar.

Since V2.1, the filename for the UIDLs can be changed. Make sure that
different POP accounts have different settings for this and everything is
OK.

@endnode

@node priority "X-Priority and Importance header fields"
The fields which are used to mark a message as important:

Eudora:
X-Priority: <number> (description)
The number is in the range 1-5. 1 Means very high, 3 means normal and 5
means very low.

MS Exchange:
Importance: <text>
Possible texts are: high, normal, low.

You can mark a message as important with the checkbox "High Priority" in
the @{"Compose mail window" link compose}.

(Low priority does not seem very useful to me.)
@endnode

@node rr "Disposition-Notification-To and Return-Receipt-To header fields"
The fields which are used to ask for a return-receipt:

Eudora:
Disposition-Notification-To: <emailaddress>
The receipt is not sent until the "unread" flag is removed. The program
will ask if you want to send a return-receipt. According to the standards,
the receipt contains what you do with the message (delete, move). This is a
violation of privacy and is not done by Eudora.

MS Exchange:
Return-Receipt-To: <emailaddress>
The receipt is sent as soon as the message has arrived.

Iris sets both in messages with return-receipt on. Return-Receipt-To is
treated as if it were Disposition-Notification-To, as it does not make sense
to send two receipts. Iris will always ask if you want to send a receipt.

Note: if you mark a message as unread, when a receipt has already been sent,
and you read the message again, Iris will ask again for a return-receipt.
In fact, this is a small error in Iris.
@endnode

@node bgui "About BGUI"
I have used the BGUI library for the GUI. As it's hard to get the library,
I have included the library (SYS:Libs/bgui.library) and a separate class
(SYS:Classes/Gadgets/bgui_popbutton.gadget) in the archive. It is version
41.8. Versions lower than 41 do not suffice due to the extensive use of
multi-column listviews. 41.x versions earlier than 41.8 may cause crashes.

NOTE: In the guide of Iris V1.0 I wrote erroneously that I didn't have the
Standard version.

Manuel Lemos <mlemos@acm.org> took over the development of BGUI recently,
with a team. The website is: @{"http://bgui.e-na.net/" system "OpenURL http://bgui.e-na.net/"} (OpenURL). There is
also a mailing list on which, besides other things, releases are announced.
Details about it are on the web site. A new version 41.11 has been uploaded
to Aminet (dev/gui) recently.

The preferences program included with it also works on 41.8. Note that the
"General" page and many menus don't work. Furthermore, applications written
without preferences in mind (like VirusChecker and Select_Host) do not
react to them. Another thing is that bgui.library supports per-application
preferences. Currently, you have to copy files in ENV/ENVARC:BGUI yourself
to take advantage of this. The name of the prefs file for Iris is
"ENV/ENVARC:BGUI/Iris.prefs". BGUI 41.8 (not 41.10) contains a bug that
causes the command name to be ignored (so prefs files for applications
started from the CLI will be named "Shell Process.prefs" etc.), but this is
circumvented in Iris. When you look with SnoopDOS, you may think that a
different process is opening the BGUI library. This is related to these
BGUI problems.

BGUI is a graphical user interface library, written by Jan van den Baard and
Ian J. Einman, for the Amiga computer which allows for easy, flexible and
fast GUI creation. It is based on BOOPSI (Basic Object-Oriented Programming
System for Intuition) and consists of a shared library which is easy to
install and a few separate files. They are, however, clearly named and
limited in number as opposed to ClassAct's and especially MUI's separate
files.

- Programmers:

    * BGUI gives you the ability to easily create automatically font
      sensitive and resizable windows.  You won't use gadtools.library
      again!

    * BGUI handles input and notification; your application can almost
      run by itself.

    * BGUI interfaces can adapt to user preferences, and localize
      themselves.

    * BGUI comes with enough object classes to get you going, and third
      parties have written classes as well.  Example source is included to
      show you how to write your own.

    * BGUI is free! No license or fees required for shareware or commercial
      usage.

- Users:

    * BGUI interfaces are font sensitive, resizable, often localized, and
      can adjust to your preferences.

    * BGUI has far smaller memory and disk requirements than other GUI
      systems, while retaining the most important features.

    * Many BGUI applications include everything you need to get started,
      there is rarely a need to obtain yet another file.

    * BGUI is free!

- The authors of BGUI:
    Original BGUI resources      - Jan van den Baard
    BGUI C headers and libraries - Ian J. Einman
    BGUI AmigaE modules          - Dominique Dutoit (ddutoit@arcadis.be)

It's difficult to find BGUI stuff on the Internet too. Ian J. Einman thought
it was better not to upload the BGUI beta versions to Aminet. Therefore the
version included with Iris cannot be found in a separate archive.
@endnode

@node asyncio "AsyncIO"
short:    AsyncIO library for fast IO. V39.2
uploader: cmh@lls.se (Magnus Holmgren)
type:     dev/c

This link library (optionally shared library) provides DOS-like functions
for using double buffered asyncronous IO on files. This provides very good
performance on DMA devices.

The code was originally written by Martin Taillefer. A few bug fixes and
updates were made by Magnus Holmgren, with inspiration from Olaf 'Olsen'
Barthel.

News in version 39.2:

	Fixed bugs in ReadLineAsync(), ReadCharAsync() and WriteCharAsync().

	SeekAsync() is now more DOS-compatible, in that it allows seeks to
	succeed after seeks past EOF. Thus, it is now possible to seek back
	to a valid position in the file and continue reading there.

News in version 39.1:

	A bugfix in SeekAsync() needed fixing. ;)

	Docs cleaned up.

	Various other minor changes.

@endnode

@node arexx "The ARexx interface"
Iris has an ARexx interface. The commands use standard ReadArgs() templates.
If there are no arguments listed, everything you put after the command is
ignored. However, this can change in future versions, so do not rely on this.

Another thing which you should take care of, is errors. Even commands which
are listed in this guide as "cannot return error" could do so in future
versions. The GET#? commands that return data can't fail, except as noted.
LOCKGUI failures can be ignored too. For the rest, always check for errors
and abort if one is encountered.

Unknown commands are treated as script names. For instance typing irisshell
in a window of IrisShell.irx will open yet another IrisShell window,
synchronously.

All commands must be in upper case, except for scripts.

@{"Examples" link rx_examples}

@{b}@{u}General command naming rules:@{uu}@{ub}

ASK<x>: opens a requester to ask the user a value for <x>
GET<x>: returns the current value of <x> (except for GETMAIL)
SET<x>: sets <x> to a value

@{b}@{u}General error RC:@{uu}@{ub}

RC=20: Iris is shutting down (unlikely).
RC=10: bad arguments. The precise error is displayed in the ARexx output
       window.
RC=5 : unknown command or script

@{b}@{u}List of commands:@{uu}@{ub}

@{b}?@{ub}
Gives the list of commands with their templates in RESULT.

@{b}READMESSAGE FILENAME/A,TYPE/N/A,FLAG,TO/K,DELETE/S@{ub}
This command is used by the asynchronous mail getting. It automatically
handles folder selection. If the TYPE parameter is 0, the message is put in
an IN folder. If the TYPE parameter is 1, it is put in an OUT folder. The
FLAG is the same as the leftmost column of the message list: * means
unread, S means unsent, space (the default) means nothing special. Do not
supply other flags to prevent collisions with future versions.

New in V1.1 is the TO parameter. This specifies the folder into which the
message is put. The command fails with RC=10 if the parameter is wrong.
(folder not found or folder of wrong type) The comparison is
case-sensitive. Use quotes.

The DELETE switch (V2.0) causes the source file (FILENAME) to be removed
after it has been copied. If it is located on the same volume it is renamed
instead of copied and deleted, which is faster.

As of V2.3, this command returns a result. It looks like
"@{i}NNNNNNNN MM Name@{ui}", in which @{i}Name@{ui} is the destination folder.

@{b}QUIT@{ub}
Quits the program. This should not be used in scripts started from Iris in
versions before 2.1.

@{b}LOADCONFIG FILE/A@{ub}
Loads a new configuration file. Since V2.0, FILE is optional, and defaults
to "PROGDIR:Iris.cfg", in which "Iris" may be replaced with the CONFIG
tooltype or command line argument. LOADCONFIG without argument is the same
as the "Last saved default" menu item.

@{b}SAVECONFIG FILE/A@{ub}
Saves a configuration file. Since V2.0, FILE is optional. SAVECONFIG
without argument is the same as the Save button in the Configuration
window.

@{b}GETCFGNAME@{ub}
Returns the current CONFIG setting. If no CONFIG options or SETCFGNAME
commands are used, this is "Iris". See @{"multiple configurations" link multicfg}.

@{b}SETCFGNAME NAME/A@{ub}
Changes the CONFIG setting, which is initialized to "Iris" or the CONFIG
CLI argument or tooltype. The indicated configuration (ENV:@{i}NAME@{ui}.cfg or
PROGDIR:@{i}NAME@{ui}.cfg) is loaded, if it exists. The name will be set in
any case. (This is another way to create a new configuration.) RC=5
indicates that neither file (see above) could be found.

@{b}GETMAIL@{ub} (strange name!)
Starts checking for new mail. Currently, there is no easy way to determine
via ARexx whether it's finished.

@{b}SENDMAIL IMMED/S@{ub}
Starts sending mail. If the IMMED switch is on, no window will appear if there
is no mail to send.

@{b}NEWMSG TO,SUBJECT@{ub}
Starts the composition of a new message.

@{b}REGISTER@{ub}
Pops up the registration form window.

@{b}INFO@{ub}
Returns the X-Mailer string, including "X-Mailer: ".

@{b}GETPROGDIR@{ub}
Returns the fully qualified name of the directory containing the Iris
executable (PROGDIR:). This directory also contains all config files
(#?.cfg) accessible via the SETCFGNAME command. Note that this might
contain spaces.

@{b}LOCKGUI@{ub}
Locks the GUI. This must be explicitely undone with UNLOCKGUI, as many times
as LOCKGUI has been executed. When the GUI is locked, you are sure that the
selection in the message list will not change, except because of ARexx
commands. The window gets a busypointer. The use of this command is not
necessary for requesters that are produced by ARexx commands.

@{b}UNLOCKGUI@{ub}
Unlocks the GUI. Executing UNLOCKGUI when no LOCKGUI has been executed can
cause trouble. (The window is not locked though it should be because a
subwindow is open. I have, however, never experienced crashes because of it.)

@{b}REBUILD@{ub}
@{"Rebuilds" link readmail} the current folder's list. In event of errors, a requester will pop
up and no error is returned, currently.

@{b}ASKSCREEN SELECTED@{ub}
Asks for a public screen. If the user cancels, RC will be 10.

@{b}GETSCREEN@{ub}
Returns the name of the public screen Iris is on. This should be used for
requesters that Iris doesn't offer via ARexx (file, directory, string etc.).

@{b}ASKCHOICE TITLE/A,BODY/A,GADGETS/A@{ub}
Pops up a requester. Separate the lines in the body with a linefeed (*N in
quotes; '0a'x ends ReadArgs and causes an error: required argument missing)
and the gadgets with a vertical bar ('|'). There is an exception to this:
%[ at the start of the gadgets will create XEN buttons and %] should create
fuzz buttons. %] Does not work, however. If you don't use %[ or %], the
type defined in the BGUI preferences for "Button" will be used. You can use
the underscore ('_') to define keyboard shortcuts. An asterisk before a
button will add Return as a shortcut key for that button and Esc for the
last button. The keyboard shortcuts LAmiga-V for the first button and
LAmiga-B for the last button are always present. Examples:

'ASKCHOICE "Start TCP/IP" "The TCP/IP stack is*Nup and running.*NDo you ,
want to*Ncheck for new*Nmail?" "**_Yes|_No"'

'ASKCHOICE "DeleteAllMsgs" "Do you want to delete all*Nmessages in this ,
folder?" "%[_Yes|_No"'

(In a script, ARexx discards the comma and the newline following it.)
Return values:
RC=5: the right button (usually: Cancel/No/Abort)
RC=0: the other buttons; The number of the button (1...n-1) is in RESULT.

@{b}GO L=LIST/S,M=MESSAGE=T=TEXT/S@{ub}
Sets the active page. Please note that the selected message is not loaded in
the window!

@{b}FOLDERNAME NUMBER/N/A@{ub}
Returns the name of folder @{i}NUMBER@{ui}. @{i}NUMBER@{ui} range is 0..N-1.
If @{i}NUMBER@{ui} is wrong, RC will be 10.

@{b}ASKFOLDER SELECTED@{ub}
Lets the user select a folder; the name is returned in RESULT. If the user
cancels, RC will be 10.

@{b}GETFOLDER@{ub}
Returns the name of the current folder.

@{b}SETFOLDER NAME/A,FORCERELOAD/S@{ub}
Sets a new current folder. The FORCERELOAD switch causes the headers file
to be read again even if the folder is already shown. Wrong name -> RC=10
(It's case sensitive!)

@{b}ASKSORTKEY@{ub}
Puts up the "sortmethod" requester. If the requester is cancelled, RC will
be 10. Otherwise, the number of the key is returned. Numbering starts at 0
for the top gadget.

@{b}GETSORTKEY@{ub}
Returns the active sort key.

@{b}SETSORTKEY NUMBER/A@{ub}
Sets a new sort key. If the number is out of range, RC will be 10.

@{b}SELECTMESSAGE NUMBER/A/N@{ub}
Selects a message in the message list. Counting starts at zero.

@{b}GETNUMSELECTED@{ub}
Returns the number of selected messages in the list.

@{b}MESSAGEFILE NUMBER/N@{ub}
Returns the filename (full path) of the selected message; if there is no
selected message, RC will be 10. If the message file is not present
(strange error), RC will be 9. New in V1.3 is the @{i}NUMBER@{ui} parameter.
It is used to get one file from multiple selection. As always, the first one
is 0. If @{i}NUMBER@{ui} is omitted and there are multiple messages selected,
an error (RC=10) will be returned.

@{b}MESSAGEINFO NUMBER/N@{ub}
Returns the selected entry in the list; tabs separate fields. Again RC=10
means that there is no selected message. You should not make any assumptions
about which fields are in this string. A date field may be added in the
future. The @{i}NUMBER@{ui} is the same as that of MESSAGEFILE.

@{b}DELETE@{ub}
Deletes the selected message(s), without confirmation requesters.
Error codes:
RC=11 -> no selection
RC=10 -> no messages could be deleted
RC=5  -> not all messages could be deleted

@{b}MOVE TO/A@{ub}
Moves the selected message(s) to the folder TO. Error codes:
RC=11 -> no selection
RC=10 -> no messages could be moved, or an invalid folder name
RC=5  -> not all messages could be moved
RC=1  -> you're trying to move to the same folder :-)

@{b}ARCHIVE@{ub}
@{"Archives" link readmail} the selected message(s). Error codes:
RC=11 -> no selection
RC=10 -> archive operation failed

@{b}RESTOREARC@{ub}
Restores all archived messages in the current folder. Error codes:
RC=10 -> an error occured while restoring the archive
RC=5  -> there are no archived messages in this folder.

@{b}WRITEMAILCAP@{ub}
Shows the loaded @{"mailcap" link cf_mailcap} information in a window. This can be used to help
find errors in the mailcap file or bugs in Iris.
@endnode

@node rx_examples "ARexx examples"
@{u}Poll.irx@{uu}

This script periodically checks for new mail (only if TCP: and Iris are
present). The period is 3 minutes, but this can be changed. Default installed
in the @{"user menu" link cf_gui} already.

@{u}DelFolder.irx@{uu}

This script deletes all messages in a folder. Before this is done, 
confirmation is sought. Default installed in the @{"user menu" link cf_gui} already. This script
was created because the incremental updating of the message list made
deletion of many messages slow. As of V1.10 it is no longer necessary, in
fact. If there are archived messages, these are deleted too; "List/Select
all" followed by Delete does not do this.

@{u}MoveMsg.irx@{uu}

This script moves the selected message(s) to another folder. Intended to be
included in the @{"user menu" link cf_gui}. Remark: doesn't work with older version of Iris
(before V1.3). As of V2.0 this script is obsolete, but it's still a good
example.

@{u}StoreMsg.irx@{uu}

This is a version of MoveMsg.irx in which the destination folder is fixed to
"Store". "Store" is part of the default configuration. As of V2.0 this
script is obsolete, but it's still a good example. For the same function
under 2.0: MOVE 'Store'. This is faster, although the error messages are
more vague.

@{u}IrisShell.irx@{uu}

This script lets you type commands to send to Iris. Beware with the DELETE
command, of course.

@{u}SelectCfg.irx@{uu}

This script lets you select a new config to be used. It requires
rexxbgui.library (Aminet: util/rexx/RexxBGUI.lha). It does a directory
listing of all saved config files, the selection and a @{"SETCFGNAME" link arexx}
command. See also @{"multiple configurations" link multicfg}.

@{u}Install_Buttons@{uu}

This script causes Iris to use a new button set. This is done with hard links.

@{u}IrisRMail.irx@{uu} (not meant to be started from the user menu)

This script simply reads a message into Iris. If Iris isn't running, it will
be started first. The path of Iris in the script may need correction. The
main use of this script is @{"smtpd" link smtpd}.
@endnode

@node cli "CLI interface"
@{u}Template:@{uu} @{b}POP/S,PDELALL/S,CURFOL/N,REPLY,MAILTO,SUBJECT,SMTP/S,SMTP-I/S,
PUBSCREEN/K,FWD/S,CONFIG/K@{ub}

@{b}POP/S@{ub} - Get mail.
@{b}PDELALL/S@{ub} - Delete all mail on server. (Same as POP with 'Delete
                     mail from server' option on)
@{b}CURFOL/N@{ub} - Set the current folder. Numbers start at zero.
@{b}REPLY@{ub} - Reply to this message. It needs a @{"MESSAGEINFO" link arexx} result.
                 This line must come from the folder indicated by CURFOL!
                 If you supply "", it just specifies that the @{"Compose window" link compose}
                 must come up.
                 I do not recommend using this, except if used with "".
@{b}MAILTO@{ub} - Set the To: address and the Subject field.
@{b}SUBJECT@{ub} - Override the default subject (mailto:... or empty string)
@{b}SMTP/S@{ub} - Send mail; an error window will pop up if there is no mail to send.
@{b}SMTP-I/S@{ub} - Send mail, without an error window if there is no mail to send.
@{b}PUBSCREEN/K@{ub} - Set the public screen for opening windows on.
@{b}FWD/S@{ub} - Use with REPLY to indicate that this is not a reply but a forward.
                 Do not use in other cases.
@{b}CONFIG/K@{ub} - See @{"multiple configurations" link multicfg}.

Inclusion of any of REPLY, MAILTO, SUBJECT will cause the @{"Compose window" link compose}
to pop up. This may be combined with SMTP to send the message immediately.
Usage of any of these options (except CURFOL, PUBSCREEN, FWD and CONFIG) will
inhibit @{"mail reading" link readmail} and the @{"ARexx interface" link arexx}.
@endnode

@node shareware "Shareware"
Iris is shareware. This program may freely be distributed as long as the
archive is kept complete and no changes are made to the files. For inclusion
on CD-ROMs, please contact me.
The differences between the freeware version and the registered version:
* @{"X-Mailer and X-Registered header fields" link compose}
* Requesters at program start and end
* Text in "About"
* A keyfile

If you want to have a keyfile, send me the registration form (the program
can generate this for you) and 5 US$, 10 DM or (preferrably) 10 NLG or a
similar amount in another currency. Please send me only notes. In response,
I will send a personalised keyfile, by email. If serious bugs show up, I will
send all registered users a fixed version. You will also get at least one new
version. (If you don't receive the keyfile within a reasonable time or
if you lose the keyfile, mail me to ask to send it again.)
The keyfile is personal and may not be given to others.

If you don't like to give your (physical) address to me, leave out the name of
the street, etc. The E-mail address is essential, however! I promise not to
pass either your address or your email address to anyone.

My address is:

E-Mail: tjoelker@zonnet.nl
